def load_data(path):
    """ Helper function for loading a MAT-File"""
    data = loadmat(path)
    return data['X'], data['y']

def plot_images(img, labels, nrows, ncols):
    """ Plot nrows x ncols images
    """
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows, ncols)
    for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flat): 
        if img[i].shape == (32, 32, 3):
            ax.imshow(img[i])
        else:
            ax.imshow(img[i,:,:,0])
        ax.set_xticks([]); ax.set_yticks([])
        ax.set_title(labels[i])

In [208]:
def rgb2gray(images):
    return np.expand_dims(np.dot(images, [0.2990, 0.5870, 0.1140]), axis=3)

val_greyscale_norm = (val_greyscale - train_mean) / train_std

Helper function for plotting the results when we are predicting the labels It randomly selects the images . This plots the nrows and mcols.¶

In [0]:
def plot_images(images, nrows, ncols, cls_true, cls_pred=None):
    """ Create figure with nrows and ncols
    """
    # Initializing the subplots
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows, ncols)
    
    # Randomly selecting nrows * ncols images
    rs = np.random.choice(images.shape[0], nrows*ncols)
    
    
    for i, ax in zip(rs, axes.flat): 
        
        # If the predictions are not passed
        if cls_pred is None:
            title = "True: {0}".format(np.argmax(cls_true[i]))
        
        # When predictions are passed, this displays the prediction and labels in images
        else:
            title = "True: {0}, Pred: {1}".format(np.argmax(cls_true[i]), cls_pred[i])  
            
        # Displays the image
        ax.imshow(images[i,:,:,0], cmap='binary')
        
        # Image annotating
        ax.set_title(title)
        
        # Setting for not overlaying the grid
        ax.set_xticks([])
        ax.set_yticks([])

The batch size is defined which the subset size of the training sample and used to train the network.¶

In [0]:
def get_batch(X, y, batch_size=512):
    for i in np.arange(0, y.shape[0], batch_size):
        end = min(X.shape[0], i + batch_size)
        yield(X[i:end],y[i:end])

Convolutional neural network architecture function.The first input layer is defined. There are two convolutional layers, two relu. The next layer has dropout and finally there is fully connected layer and relu. We have used strides which is 2 and applied relu function to remove elements which are negative¶

def cnn_model_fn(features): """Model function for CNN."""

  # Input Layer
input_layer = tf.reshape(features, [-1, 32, 32, 1], name='Reshaped_Input')

  # Convolutional Layer #1
#with tf.name_scope('Conv1 Layer + ReLU'):

conv_1 = tf.layers.conv2d(
    inputs=input_layer,
    filters=32,
    kernel_size=[5, 5],
    padding="same",
    activation=tf.nn.relu)

  # Pooling Layer with 2x2 matrix by 2 cells and stride 2
pool_1 = tf.layers.max_pooling2d(inputs=conv_1, pool_size=[2, 2], strides=2)

  # Convolutional Layer #2 and Pooling Layer #2
conv_2 = tf.layers.conv2d(
      inputs=pool_1,
      filters=64,
      kernel_size=[5, 5],
      padding="same",
      activation=tf.nn.relu)

Pooling Layer with 2x2 matrix by 2 cells and stride 2¶

pool_2 = tf.layers.max_pooling2d(inputs=conv_2, pool_size=[2, 2], strides=2)

  # Dense and dropout layer
pool2flat = tf.reshape(pool_2, [-1, 8 * 8 * 64])
dense = tf.layers.dense(inputs=pool2flat, units=256, activation=tf.nn.relu)
dropout = tf.layers.dropout(
     inputs=dense, rate=discard_rate)

  # Logits Layer
logits_pred = tf.layers.dense(inputs=dropout, units=10)

return logits_pred

In [0]:
def evaluate_batch(test, batch_size):
    """ Evaluate in batches 
    """
    # Store the cumulative accuracy over all batches
    cumulative_accuracy = 0.0
    
    # Get the number of images
    n_images = y_test.shape[0] if test else y_val.shape[0]
    
    # Numer of batches needed to evaluate all images
    n_batches = n_images // batch_size + 1
    
    # Iterate over all the batches
    for i in range(n_batches):
        
        # Calculate the offset
        offset = i * batch_size
     
        if test:
            # Get the batch from the test set
            xs, ys = X_test[offset:offset+batch_size], y_test[offset:offset+batch_size]
        else:
            # Get batch from the validation set
            xs, ys = X_val[offset:offset+batch_size], y_val[offset:offset+batch_size]
            
        cumulative_accuracy += sess.run(accuracy,
                {x: xs, y: ys})
                                           
    # Return the average accuracy over all batches
    return cumulative_accuracy / float(n_batches)

def flatten(lists):
    results = []
    for numbers in lists:
        for x in numbers:
            results.append(x)
    return np.asarray(results)

def load_data(path):
    """ Helper function for loading a MAT-File"""
    data = loadmat(path)
    return data['X'], data['y']

def plot_images(img, labels, nrows, ncols):
    """ Plot nrows x ncols images
    """
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows, ncols)
    for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flat): 
        if img[i].shape == (32, 32, 3):
            ax.imshow(img[i])
        else:
            ax.imshow(img[i,:,:,0])
        ax.set_xticks([]); ax.set_yticks([])
        ax.set_title(labels[i])

def plot_images(images, nrows, ncols, cls_true, cls_pred=None):
    """ Create figure with nrows and ncols
    """
    # Initializing the subplots
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows, ncols)
    
    # Randomly selecting nrows * ncols images
    rs = np.random.choice(images.shape[0], nrows*ncols)
    
    
    for i, ax in zip(rs, axes.flat): 
        
        # If the predictions are not passed
        if cls_pred is None:
            title = "True: {0}".format(np.argmax(cls_true[i]))
        
        # When predictions are passed, this displays the prediction and labels in images
        else:
            title = "True: {0}, Pred: {1}".format(np.argmax(cls_true[i]), cls_pred[i])  
            
        # Displays the image
        ax.imshow(images[i,:,:,0], cmap='binary')
        
        # Image annotating
        ax.set_title(title)
        
        # Setting for not overlaying the grid
        ax.set_xticks([])
        ax.set_yticks([])

def get_batch(X, y, batch_size=512):
    for i in np.arange(0, y.shape[0], batch_size):
        end = min(X.shape[0], i + batch_size)
        yield(X[i:end],y[i:end])

    conv1 = tf.layers.conv2d(
        inputs=input_layer,
        filters=32,
        kernel_size=[5, 5],
        padding="same",
        activation=tf.nn.relu)

      # Pooling Layer with 2x2 matrix by 2 cells and stride 2
    pool1 = tf.layers.max_pooling2d(inputs=conv1, pool_size=[2, 2], strides=2)

      # Convolutional Layer #2 and Pooling Layer #2
    conv2 = tf.layers.conv2d(
          inputs=pool1,
          filters=64,
          kernel_size=[5, 5],
          padding="same",
          activation=tf.nn.relu)
        
   ## Pooling Layer with 2x2 matrix by 2 cells and stride 2
    pool2 = tf.layers.max_pooling2d(inputs=conv2, pool_size=[2, 2], strides=2)

      # Dense and dropout layer
    pool2_flat = tf.reshape(pool2, [-1, 8 * 8 * 64])
    dense = tf.layers.dense(inputs=pool2_flat, units=256, activation=tf.nn.relu)
    dropout = tf.layers.dropout(
         inputs=dense, rate=discard_rate)

      # Logits Layer
    logits = tf.layers.dense(inputs=dropout, units=10)

    return logits

def evaluate_batch(test, batch_size):
    """ Evaluate in batches 
    """
    # Store the cumulative accuracy over all batches
    cumulative_accuracy = 0.0
    
    # Get the number of images
    n_images = y_test.shape[0] if test else y_val.shape[0]
    
    # Numer of batches needed to evaluate all images
    n_batches = n_images // batch_size + 1
    
    # Iterate over all the batches
    for i in range(n_batches):
        
        # Calculate the offset
        offset = i * batch_size
     
        if test:
            # Get the batch from the test set
            xs, ys = X_test[offset:offset+batch_size], y_test[offset:offset+batch_size]
        else:
            # Get batch from the validation set
            xs, ys = X_val[offset:offset+batch_size], y_val[offset:offset+batch_size]
            
        cumulative_accuracy += sess.run(accuracy,
                {x: xs, y: ys})
                                           
    # Return the average accuracy over all batches
    return cumulative_accuracy / float(n_batches)

    results = []
    for numbers in lists:
        for x in numbers:
            results.append(x)
    return np.asarray(results)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.style.use('ggplot')

def plot_history(history):
    acc = history.history['acc']
    val_acc = history.history['val_acc']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    x = range(1, len(acc) + 1)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(x, acc, 'b', label='Training acc')
    plt.plot(x, val_acc, 'r', label='Validation acc')
    plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(x, loss, 'b', label='Training loss')
    plt.plot(x, val_loss, 'r', label='Validation loss')
    plt.title('Training and validation loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.style.use('ggplot')

def plot_history(history):
    acc = history.history['acc']
    val_acc = history.history['val_acc']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    x = range(1, len(acc) + 1)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(x, acc, 'b', label='Training acc')
    plt.plot(x, val_acc, 'r', label='Validation acc')
    plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(x, loss, 'b', label='Training loss')
    plt.plot(x, val_loss, 'r', label='Validation loss')
    plt.title('Training and validation loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()


plot_history(batch_model)

# X are the pixels of the images and y are the corresponding labels.
def load_data(path):
    """ Helper function for loading a MAT-File"""
    data = loadmat(path)
    return data['X'], data['y']

X_train, y_train = load_data('train_32x32.mat')
X_test, y_test = load_data('test_32x32.mat')

print("Training Set", X_train.shape, y_train.shape)
print("Test Set", X_test.shape, y_test.shape)

# Calculating optimal k to have 95% (say) variance 
k = 0
total = sum(pca.explained_variance_)
current_sum = 0

while(current_sum / total < 0.99):
    current_sum += pca.explained_variance_[k]
    k += 1
k
